Impact of the COVID-19 Pandemic on Hypertension Prescriptions Across Scotland

Evie Andrewes

2024-11-25

From the 2011 to the 2022 census, there was an additional 80,700 people in Scotland who reported bad or very bad health. This is thought to be due to an aging population (Wroth-Smith 2024). One of the most common age-related diseases is hypertension (high blood pressure) (Inform 2024). This report will aim to deduce if during the COVID-19 pandemic there was a significant increase in prescriptions for hypertension across Scotland.

1 Hypertension Perscriptions Across Scotland

1.1 First Steps

Before we start exploring prescriptions for hypertension, lets load in the libraries needed.

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(gt) 
library(here)
library(sf)

1.2 Exploring and Filtering our Data

To begin, lets look at the number of prescriptions of common hypertension medications, like doxazosin, amlodipine, bisoprolol and atenolol (Inform 2024), in a month for each health board in Scotland pre-pandemic (August 2019) and post-pandemic (August 2022).

`load_clean_data` <- function(url) {
  read_csv(url) %>%
    clean_names()} 
#Creates a function so loading and cleaning data from a url can be streamlined. This will be useful throughout the project.

data_and_hbs <- c(
  "data_august2019" = "https://www.opendata.nhs.scot/dataset/84393984-14e9-4b0d-a797-b288db64d088/resource/5c667230-4201-4a09-949d-3e6cc3a4ec19/download/pitc201908.csv",
  "data_august2022" = "https://www.opendata.nhs.scot/dataset/84393984-14e9-4b0d-a797-b288db64d088/resource/49fa5784-be06-4015-bc6d-9b5db8726473/download/pitc202208.csv",
  "HB_fullnames" = "https://www.opendata.nhs.scot/dataset/9f942fdb-e59e-44f5-b534-d6e17229cc7b/resource/652ff726-e676-4a20-abda-435b98dd7bdc/download/hb14_hb19.csv")

clean_datasets_with_hbs <- data_and_hbs %>% 
  map(~ load_clean_data(.x))
#Here the map function is loading and cleaning all of the data.

joined_datasets <- c("data_august2019", "data_august2022") %>% 
  map(~ clean_datasets_with_hbs[[.x]] %>%
    full_join(clean_datasets_with_hbs$HB_fullnames,by = if (.x == "data_august2019") c("hbt2014" = "hb") else c("hbt" = "hb")) %>%
      select(hb_name, bnf_item_description, paid_quantity))
#Here map is used to pull the datasets that we want from the data that was loaded in. They are joined by HB name (depending on what this variable is called). We use [[]] for .x because it is a changing or dynamic variable.

hypertension_drugs <- c(
  "DOXAZOSIN" = "Doxazosin Prescriptions", 
  "BISOPROLOL" = "Bisoprolol Prescriptions", 
  "AMLODIPINE" = "Amlodipine Prescriptions", 
  "ATENOLOL" = "Atenolol Prescriptions")
# Here a named vector is created for our hypertension drugs.

combined_hypertension_summary <- joined_datasets %>%
  map2_df(c(2019, 2022), ~ .x %>%
    mutate(drug_type = str_extract(bnf_item_description, paste(names(hypertension_drugs), collapse = "|")),
           drug_type = hypertension_drugs[drug_type]) %>%
    filter(!is.na(drug_type)) %>%
    group_by(hb_name, drug_type) %>%
    summarize(total_paid_quantity = sum(paid_quantity)) %>%
      mutate(year = .y))
#Now the named vector can be used to pull out the drugs of interest using names and str_extract. This returns the value we want instead of TRUE/FALSE like str_detect.The year column is created using the second input of the map2_df function (y).

The prescription and health board data has been filtered to show the number of each hypertension medication for each health board in August 2019 and August 2022. Now lets plot a lollipop chart that shows the difference between the number of prescriptions in August 2019 and August 2022 to see how theyve changed.

combined_hypertension_summary_diff <- combined_hypertension_summary %>%
  group_by(hb_name, drug_type) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = year, values_from = total_paid_quantity) %>%
  mutate(diff = `2022` - `2019`) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(diff))

hypertension_plot <- ggplot(combined_hypertension_summary_diff, aes(x = diff, y = hb_name, color = drug_type)) +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = 0, yend = hb_name), linewidth = 0.5) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Difference in Hypertension Prescriptions from August 2019 to August 2022", subtitle = "by Health Board and Drug Type", x = "Change in Total Perscriptions", y = "Health Board", color = "Drug Type") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::label_number()) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5), axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

hypertension_plot

1.3 Chart Results

All of the drugs show a significant increase in prescriptions from 2019 to 2022 apart from atenolol. This is because atenolol and bisoprolol are both beta-blockers, but bisoprolol has shown to be more heart specific and therefore it has less side effects. This means that many providers have been switching patients to bisoprolol in recent years (Allen 2024). There is an especially significant increase in hypertension prescriptions in NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde and NHS Lothian. Lets take a clearer look at the data from these areas by displaying it in a table.

hypertension_table <- combined_hypertension_summary_diff %>%
  filter(hb_name %in% c("NHS Lothian", "NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde")) %>%
  gt(rowname_col = "drug_type", groupname_col = "hb_name") %>%
  tab_header(title = "Hypertension Perscriptions in August for Hypertension from 2019 to 2022", subtitle = "Data from NHS Lothian and NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde") %>% 
  cols_label(hb_name = "Health Board Name",
    drug_type = "Drug Type",
    diff = "Difference in Perscriptions",
   `2019` = "August 2019",
   `2022` = "August 2022") %>% 
  cols_align(align = "center", columns = diff) %>% 
  fmt_number(n_sigfig = 4, sep_mark = ",", decimals = 0) %>% 
  summary_rows(columns = diff, fns = list("Total Difference" = ~sum(.)), formatter = fmt_number, decimals = 0) %>%
  grand_summary_rows(columns = diff, fns = list("Overall Difference" = ~sum(.)), formatter = fmt_number, decimals = 0)

1.4 Table Results

From this table, you can see the number of prescriptions in a month for hypertension has increased by 600,000 from August 2019 to August 2022 in NHS Lothian and Greater Glasgow and Clyde alone. This indicates a huge increase in hypertension prescriptions over the COVID-19 pandemic in these areas.

However, it is also known these areas are very well populated within Scotland, so it is unknown how proportional this increase is to the general population. Lets load in some data about population size per health board, and create a spatial plot to visualize this:

pop_health_board <- load_clean_data("https://www.opendata.nhs.scot/dataset/7f010430-6ce1-4813-b25c-f7f335bdc4dc/resource/27a72cc8-d6d8-430c-8b4f-3109a9ceadb1/download/hb2019_pop_est_14102024.csv")

pop_health_board_filtered <- pop_health_board %>% 
  select(year, hb, all_ages) %>% 
  filter(year == "2019" | year == "2022")

health_board_spatial_data <- st_read(here("data","NHS_healthboards_2019.shp")) %>% 
  clean_names()

total_hypertension_prescriptions <- combined_hypertension_summary %>%  group_by(hb_name, year) %>%
  summarize(total_paid_quantity_all_drugs = sum(total_paid_quantity)) 

total_hypertension_prescriptions <- total_hypertension_prescriptions %>%
  mutate(hb_name = str_remove(hb_name, "^NHS\\s"))

combined_spatial_data <- health_board_spatial_data %>% 
  full_join(pop_health_board_filtered, by = c("hb_code" = "hb")) %>%
  full_join(total_hypertension_prescriptions, by = c("hb_name" = "hb_name","year" = "year")) %>%
  mutate(prescriptions_per_capita = total_paid_quantity_all_drugs / all_ages)

Now that the number of hypertension prescriptions per capita in each health board has been combined with spacial data, a plot can be created.

ggplot(data = combined_spatial_data) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = prescriptions_per_capita)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(name = "Prescriptions per Capita") +
  facet_wrap(~ year) +
  theme_void() +
  labs(title = "Hypertension Prescriptions per Capita per Month", subtitle = "Health Boards in Scotland (August 2019 & August 2022)") +
  theme(legend.position = "right", plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
